        <h2 id="deposit">Deposit</h2>

        <h3>Who can deposit</h3>

        <p>We accept deposits from affiliates of Columbia University, Barnard College, Jewish Theological Seminary, Teachers College, and Union Theological Seminary.</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Current faculty and staff</li>
          <li>Emeritus faculty</li>
          <li>Retired faculty (still in directory?)</li>
          <li>Departments, centers, and programs</li>
          <li>Some degree programs encourage or require students to deposit their thesis or capstone project in Academic Commons. Students may also be able to deposit other work. For more information, see the section on student works, below.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Eligible content</h3>

        <h4>Results of research and scholarship</h4>
        <p>Academic Commons accepts the digital results of research and scholarship created at Columbia and its affiliate institutions.</p>

        <h4>Deposit agreement</h4>
        <p>Depositors must confirm that they have sufficient rights to deposit the work in Academic Commons. As part of the deposit process, authors/creators agree to grant Columbia University a non-exclusive license to distribute their work in Academic Commons. By signing this agreement, authors affirm that they hold sufficient rights to grant this license.</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Read our copyright information to learn more.</li>
          <li>Read about managing copyrights to your work by visiting the Copyright Advisory Office website.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Shareable “as is”</h4>
        <p>We expect that the work you deposit is ready to share online “as is.” If you create a new version of the work at a later date, you can deposit the new version as well. We will retain both versions and create links between them in repository metadata.</p>

        <h4>Protects privacy and confidentiality</h4>
        <p>Deposited works must be in compliance with all relevant federal, state, and institutional policies and guidelines regarding the protection of privacy and confidentiality of human subjects. Works that should not be openly available online should not be deposited in Academic Commons.</p>

        <h3>File formats</h3>

        <h4>All file types accepted</h4>
        <p>We accept any type of file, though we encourage depositors to use formats which are non-proprietary and can be opened and used in a variety of platforms and applications (for example, a csv file is preferable to one in Excel).</p>

        <h4>Files larger than 100MB</h4>
        Our self-deposit form accepts individual files up to 100MB. If you have larger files to deposit, contact us and we will arrange an alternative method of transfer.

        <h4>Deposit fee for files over 10GB</h4>
        You can deposit individual files up to 10GB free of charge. There is a one-time fee of $5 per GB for individual files that are over 10GB and up to 100GB in size. This fee is payable at the time of deposit. If you have individual files larger than 100GB, please contact us.

        <h3>How to deposit</h3>

        <h4>Self-deposit form</h4>
        <p>Our <a href="/deposit/">self-deposit form</a> is appropriate if you:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>are a member of the faculty or staff.</li>
          <li>are depositing a file up to 100MB in size</li>
          <li>can easily describe your work by filling in title, author, and abstract information.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Email us</h4>
        <p>Contact us at <a href="mailto:ac@columbia.edu">ac@columbia.edu</a> if you:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>have questions.</li>
          <li>wish to deposit a large number of files at once.</li>
          <li>are making a proxy deposit.</li>
          <li>wish to arrange for an ongoing deposit of works such as student theses or working papers.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Please note that authors who submit items by email will also be required to sign our deposit agreement.</p>

        <h3>Your work in the repository</h3>

        <h4>Deposit timeline</h4>
        <p>Please allow up to a week for your deposit to become available in Academic Commons. Email us at <a href="mailto:ac@columbia.edu">ac@columbia.edu</a> if you have any questions or need to request faster processing. Authors with a Columbia UNI will receive an automatic email notification when your work is available in the repository.</p>

        <h4>Persistent identifier for each work</h4>
        <p>Each work in Academic Commons is assigned a DIgital Object Identifier (DOI), which is a type of persistent URL. A sample DOI is: 10.7916/D8ZS2W8R. DOIs expressed as URLs look like this: https://doi.org/10.7916/D8ZS2W8R. Use the DOI when citing or referring to a work in Academic Commons.</p>

        <h4>Usage statistics reports</h4>
        <p>Authors who provide a Columbia UNI will receive a monthly email showing the number of views and downloads for each of their works in Academic Commons. Contact us at <a href="mailto:ac@columbia.edu">ac@columbia.edu</a> if your are not receiving our monthly emails or if you would like us to forward the emails to a new address.</p>

        <h4>Changing works in the repository</h4>
        <p>With some exceptions, we do not change or replace files that are available in the repository. However, we can archive new versions of a work while retaining the older versions, adding metadata that links between the different versions.</p>

        <h4>Removing works from the repository</h4>
        <p>We strongly discourage the withdrawal of works from Academic Commons. However, depositors can request that public access to a work in Academic Commons be disabled. Though the work will no longer be publicly accessible, some metadata about the work will remain publicly available in Academic Commons.</p>

